I'm always the life
of the party.
[Party Favors Blowing]

679
00:49:25,028 --> 00:49:28,225
Casper, listen.
I know you want to go.

680
00:49:28,298 --> 00:49:30,289
Come on. We'd have
a great time together.

681
00:49:30,367 --> 00:49:32,528
Casper, I have a date.

682
00:49:32,602 --> 00:49:35,196
What's this Vic guy got
that I don't, huh?

683
00:49:35,272 --> 00:49:39,936
A pulse?
Big fleshy deal.

684
00:49:40,010 --> 00:49:43,002
A tan.
Very bad for your skin.

685
00:49:43,947 --> 00:49:45,972
How about a reflection?

686
00:49:50,587 --> 00:49:54,387
Okay, okay,
but can he do this?

687
00:49:56,793 --> 00:50:00,320
[Mimics Arnold Schwarzenegger]
Come with me if you want to live.

688
00:50:00,397 --> 00:50:03,298
Casper?
[Grunting]

689
00:50:03,367 --> 00:50:05,301
Casper! No! Don't!

690
00:50:05,369 --> 00:50:09,703
Casper, no!
Casper, no! No, no, no, no!

691
00:50:09,773 --> 00:50:13,766
<i>[Screaming]</i>

692
00:50:13,844 --> 00:50:16,972
Casper, no. Oh, my God!
High! This is very high!

693
00:50:17,047 --> 00:50:20,608
Casper! Casper!

694
00:50:32,262 --> 00:50:34,992
Casper,
this is beautiful.

695
00:50:35,065 --> 00:50:37,556
I come here every night.

696
00:50:37,634 --> 00:50:41,832
Alone?
Mm-hmm.

697
00:50:41,905 --> 00:50:45,841
What were you like
when you were alive?

698
00:50:45,909 --> 00:50:50,846
I was... I was...

699
00:50:50,914 --> 00:50:53,075
I don't remember.

700
00:50:54,484 --> 00:50:57,282
You don't remember
anything from your life?

701
00:50:57,354 --> 00:50:59,288
No.

702
00:50:59,356 --> 00:51:02,154
So... Nothing?

703
00:51:02,225 --> 00:51:04,284
No.

704
00:51:04,361 --> 00:51:08,525
You don't remember
what school you went to,
how old you were?

705
00:51:08,598 --> 00:51:11,328
Your favorite song?

706
00:51:11,401 --> 00:51:17,033
What about your dad?
Hm-mmm.

707
00:51:17,107 --> 00:51:19,598
Not even your mom?

708
00:51:19,676 --> 00:51:23,476
Is that bad?
No.

709
00:51:23,547 --> 00:51:26,414
It's just kind of sad.

710
00:51:34,458 --> 00:51:37,825
I wonder why you
don't remember anything.

711
00:51:37,894 --> 00:51:43,332
Hmm? Guess 'cause
when you're a ghost,

712
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:46,631
life doesn't matter
that much anymore.

713
00:51:46,703 --> 00:51:49,968
So you forget.

714
00:51:50,040 --> 00:51:54,773
Sometimes I worry
that I'm trying to forget.

715
00:51:54,845 --> 00:51:57,040
Forget what?

716
00:51:57,114 --> 00:52:01,676
My mom.
Just certain things.

717
00:52:02,886 --> 00:52:07,016
The sound of her making
breakfast downstairs.

718
00:52:07,090 --> 00:52:09,388
The way she put on
her lipstick...

719
00:52:09,426 --> 00:52:12,827
so carefully.

720
00:52:13,997 --> 00:52:18,900
I do remember...
she always used Ivory soap.

721
00:52:18,969 --> 00:52:22,166
And when she'd hug me,
I'd breathe her in...

722
00:52:22,239 --> 00:52:24,935
so deep.

723
00:52:25,008 --> 00:52:29,001
And I remember,
before I'd go to sleep,

724
00:52:29,079 --> 00:52:33,539
she'd whisper in my ear,
"Stardust in the eyes,

725
00:52:33,617 --> 00:52:37,383
rosy cheeks and a happy girl
in the morning."

726
00:52:42,559 --> 00:52:44,618
Casper?

727
00:52:46,029 --> 00:52:48,088
Hmm?

728
00:52:48,165 --> 00:52:52,966
If my mom's a ghost,
did she forget about me?

729
00:52:53,036 --> 00:52:56,494
No, she'd
never forget you.

730
00:52:58,308 --> 00:53:01,505
Kat?
Mm-hmm?

731
00:53:01,578 --> 00:53:07,312
If I were alive, would you go to
the Halloween dance with me?

732
00:53:07,384 --> 00:53:09,477
Mm-hmm.

733
00:53:09,553 --> 00:53:12,249
Kat?
Hmm?

734
00:53:12,322 --> 00:53:16,122
Can I keep you?
Mm-hmm.

735
00:53:19,296 --> 00:53:23,562
Casper, close the window.
It's cold.

736
00:53:41,184 --> 00:53:44,244
<i>[Birds Twittering]</i>

737
00:53:48,258 --> 00:53:51,227
Hey, Dad!

738
00:53:51,294 --> 00:53:53,762
Found your Visa card.

739
00:53:53,830 --> 00:53:56,025
Where was it?
Um, in your wallet.

740
00:53:56,099 --> 00:53:59,933
Maybe I could use it to buy
this perfect costume I saw
in a store downtown.

741
00:54:00,003 --> 00:54:04,667
You always
made your costume.
No, Mom did.

742
00:54:04,741 --> 00:54:08,677
I think I could come up
with something pretty good.

743
00:54:08,745 --> 00:54:13,239
Why don't we roll you
in aluminum foil, and you
could go as a leftover?

744
00:54:14,851 --> 00:54:16,910
[Muttering]

745
00:54:16,987 --> 00:54:20,081
Don't worry.
You always look cute.

746
00:54:20,156 --> 00:54:24,286
I don't wanna look cute.
Cute's like when
you're nine years old...

747
00:54:24,361 --> 00:54:27,853
and you've got papier-mache
around your head.

748
00:54:27,931 --> 00:54:33,301
I want to look... nice.
Mm-hmm.

749
00:54:33,370 --> 00:54:37,636
Like... Like date nice.

750
00:54:39,776 --> 00:54:44,406
Really? Uh...

751
00:54:44,481 --> 00:54:48,247
Honey, I think maybe
it's time that we...

752
00:54:48,318 --> 00:54:51,481
<i>sat down and</i>...
It's a little late
for that, Dad.

753
00:54:51,554 --> 00:54:57,356
- How late?
- Oh, don't worry.
Not that late.

754
00:54:57,427 --> 00:55:00,794
Oh, good.

755
00:55:00,864 --> 00:55:04,766
You know that I would love
to buy you everything you wanted.

756
00:55:04,834 --> 00:55:08,930
But until Miss Crittenden
pays me, that thing
is pretty worthless.

757
00:55:09,005 --> 00:55:12,998
Oh, well, that's okay.
Don't worry about it.

758
00:55:13,076 --> 00:55:16,102
I'm sure I can come up
with something perfect
for the party.

759
00:55:16,179 --> 00:55:19,774
<i>[Ghostly Trio]</i>
**<i>It's my party and</i>
<i>I'll die if I want to</i> **

760
00:55:19,849 --> 00:55:23,717
**<i>Die if I want to</i> **
<i>[Cackling]</i>

761
00:55:23,787 --> 00:55:27,188
Dad, please,
whatever you do,

762
00:55:27,257 --> 00:55:29,316
don't let those guys
crash it.

763
00:55:29,392 --> 00:55:34,921
Oh, no, I think they're actually
getting to be quite focused now.

764
00:55:34,998 --> 00:55:37,364
<i>[Cackling]</i>

765
00:55:37,434 --> 00:55:41,063
** <i>You will die too</i>
<i>when it happens to you</i> **

766
00:55:41,137 --> 00:55:44,368
**<i>Da, da, da-da, da, da</i> ****
<i>[Cackling]</i>

767
00:55:44,441 --> 00:55:47,535
<i>[Fatso]</i>
<i>Big finish.!</i>

768
00:55:47,610 --> 00:55:49,703
<i>[Stretch]</i>
<i>Scream or sugar?</i>

769
00:55:49,779 --> 00:55:51,713
<i>[Cackling]</i>

770
00:57:08,024 --> 00:57:12,324
<i>[Stretch, German Accent]</i>
<i>Vell, vell, ze patient</i>
<i>has finally arrived.</i>

771
00:57:12,395 --> 00:57:14,454
Late again, I see.

772
00:57:14,531 --> 00:57:17,659
Could this be an expression
of hostility, Doc?

773
00:57:17,734 --> 00:57:22,797
<i>[Cackling]</i>
<i>[Fatso]</i>
<i>It's your hour, Freud.</i>

774
00:57:24,374 --> 00:57:29,311
What? So silent?
No pearls of wisdom
today, Doc?

775
00:57:29,379 --> 00:57:33,873
Come on, Doc.
Stay tough. Don't stop.

776
00:57:33,950 --> 00:57:36,612
Come on, Doc.
Hang with us homeboys.

777
00:57:36,686 --> 00:57:39,553
Hey, wait a second.
What?

778
00:57:39,622 --> 00:57:42,614
You ain't thinkin'
about packin' it in now,
are ya, Doc?

779
00:57:42,692 --> 00:57:44,353
We were just startin'
to have fun.

780
00:57:44,394 --> 00:57:49,991
It ain't often we meet
a bonebag as amusin' as you.

781
00:57:50,066 --> 00:57:55,026
Boys, this is serious.
I think the doc is havin'
one of them fleshy breakdowns.

782
00:57:55,104 --> 00:57:56,230
<i>[Stinkie]</i>
<i>Time for drastic measures.</i>

783
00:57:56,272 --> 00:57:59,070
Think we should break
into a song?
No!

784
00:57:59,108 --> 00:58:02,703
It's time we gave the doc
our own prescription.

785
00:58:02,779 --> 00:58:05,907
What about the party?
The party will have to wait.

786
00:58:05,982 --> 00:58:09,281
Are you thinkin'
what I'm thinkin'?
Gentlemen?

787
00:58:09,352 --> 00:58:12,185
Happy hour!
Happy hour!
Happy hour.

788
00:58:12,255 --> 00:58:14,553
Whoop...
Yee-haw!

789
00:58:14,624 --> 00:58:16,649
<i>[Ghostly Trio]</i>
**<i>Ninety-nine bottles ofbeer</i>
<i>on the wall</i> **

790
00:58:16,726 --> 00:58:20,560
**<i>Ninety-nine bottles ofbeer</i> ****
<i>[Fatso]</i>
<i>Just the dead guys.!</i>

791
00:58:20,630 --> 00:58:23,190
This is an outrage.
This is appalling.

792
00:58:23,266 --> 00:58:26,292
You pay a man to get
the ghosts out of the house,
and what does he do?

793
00:58:26,369 --> 00:58:29,338
He gets the ghosts
out of the house.
Exactly.

794
00:58:42,051 --> 00:58:43,985
It's about time.

795
00:58:53,329 --> 00:58:55,524
Ohh!
Look familiar?

796
00:58:57,567 --> 00:58:59,501
This is...

797
00:59:00,570 --> 00:59:02,504
This is...

798
00:59:04,908 --> 00:59:06,842
And...

799
00:59:09,412 --> 00:59:11,346
I know this.

800
00:59:16,319 --> 00:59:18,810
I had five fingers.

801
00:59:18,888 --> 00:59:20,822
I remember!

802
00:59:20,890 --> 00:59:23,017
<i>[Train Whistle Blowing]</i>
Hootie!

803
00:59:27,697 --> 00:59:29,631
[Whistle Blowing]
<i>Chugga-chugga,</i>
<i>chugga-chugga.</i>

804
00:59:29,699 --> 00:59:31,633
And wait!

805
00:59:35,939 --> 00:59:38,965
[Thud]

806
00:59:39,042 --> 00:59:40,976
Check it out.

807
00:59:41,044 --> 00:59:42,978
<i>Hands up, Kat.</i>

808
00:59:51,854 --> 00:59:54,721
Oh, wow.
It was my mom's.

809
00:59:54,791 --> 00:59:57,385
[Sighs]

810
00:59:57,460 --> 00:59:59,655
Can I...
Go ahead.

811
01:00:11,240 --> 01:00:14,607
Oh, Casper,
it's perfect.

812
01:00:14,677 --> 01:00:17,840
You think I could wear it
to the party tonight?

813
01:00:19,349 --> 01:00:21,283
Casper?

814
01:00:27,023 --> 01:00:30,686
I begged and begged my dad
to get me this sled,

815
01:00:30,760 --> 01:00:33,456
and he acted like
I couldn't even have it,

816
01:00:33,529 --> 01:00:36,327
'cause I didn't know
how to ride it.

817
01:00:36,399 --> 01:00:39,163
And then one morning,
I... I came down
for breakfast,

818
01:00:39,235 --> 01:00:41,635
and there it was,
just for me.

819
01:00:41,704 --> 01:00:43,729
For no reason at all.

820
01:00:45,074 --> 01:00:49,340
I took it out,
went sledding all day,

821
01:00:49,412 --> 01:00:52,176
and my dad said,
"That's enough,"
but I couldn't stop.

822
01:00:52,248 --> 01:00:54,307
I was having so much fun.

823
01:00:54,384 --> 01:00:56,318
Then it got late.

824
01:00:57,387 --> 01:00:59,321
It got dark.

825
01:00:59,389 --> 01:01:01,323
Got cold.

826
01:01:02,759 --> 01:01:06,525
And I got sick.
My dad got sad.

827
01:01:14,604 --> 01:01:16,538
What's it like to die?

828
01:01:18,341 --> 01:01:21,003
Like being born.

829
01:01:22,311 --> 01:01:24,939
Only backwards.

830
01:01:25,014 --> 01:01:28,848
I remember I didn't go
where I was supposed to go.

831
01:01:28,918 --> 01:01:31,512
I just stayed behind...

832
01:01:31,587 --> 01:01:33,817
so my dad
wouldn't be lonely.

833
01:01:48,671 --> 01:01:50,730
Is that your dad?
<i>Mm-hmm.</i>

834
01:01:53,910 --> 01:01:57,869
"McFadden claimed that he
was haunted by the ghost
of his dead son,

835
01:01:57,947 --> 01:02:01,212
"and that he
invented a machine
to bring him back to life:

836
01:02:01,284 --> 01:02:03,218
The Lazarus."
The Lazarus.

837
01:02:09,325 --> 01:02:11,953
Ooh.

838
01:02:12,028 --> 01:02:16,124
Hee-hee. Sorry.
I guess we'll have
to take the long way.

839
01:02:16,199 --> 01:02:18,167
Hurry up!
Come on!

840
01:02:21,938 --> 01:02:24,998
My dad hid it
so no one can find it,
but I remember where it is!

841
01:02:25,074 --> 01:02:27,133
<i>Ha.!</i>
<i>Wait'll you see it.</i>

842
01:02:38,054 --> 01:02:40,887
- Don't you know a shortcut?
- You got it.

843
01:02:42,458 --> 01:02:46,019
Casper, no!
Wall... human?

844
01:02:46,095 --> 01:02:48,063
Stop!

845
01:02:54,036 --> 01:02:57,199
<i>Hey.! Over here.</i>

846
01:02:57,273 --> 01:02:59,207
Go ahead.
Sit down.

847
01:03:01,644 --> 01:03:04,875
I would hold on.
Why?

848
01:03:04,947 --> 01:03:06,972
<i>[Machine Clanging]</i>

849
01:03:08,785 --> 01:03:10,912
[Gasps]

850
01:03:10,987 --> 01:03:13,421
<i>[Whirring]</i>

851
01:03:13,489 --> 01:03:15,650
[Steps Clattering]

852
01:03:18,594 --> 01:03:23,725
Casper!
[Screaming]

853
01:03:25,101 --> 01:03:27,262
[Latch Clicking]

854
01:03:27,336 --> 01:03:32,000
<i>[Wind Whistling]</i>

855
01:03:32,074 --> 01:03:34,474
<i>[Eerie Laughter]</i>

856
01:03:41,017 --> 01:03:45,147
[Bell Ringing,
Electricity Crackling]

857
01:04:14,383 --> 01:04:16,943
[Gasping]

858
01:04:17,019 --> 01:04:19,817
<i>[Wind Vents Firing]</i>

859
01:04:53,923 --> 01:04:55,857
Well?

860
01:04:55,925 --> 01:04:58,587
What was that?
The "Up and At 'Em" machine.

861
01:04:58,661 --> 01:05:02,757
My dad was a great inventor,
but he had a little trouble
getting going in the morning.

862
01:05:02,832 --> 01:05:05,130
Didn't he ever hear
of caffeine?

863
01:05:06,269 --> 01:05:07,759
[Crackling]

864
01:05:07,837 --> 01:05:11,534
[Groaning]

865
01:05:11,607 --> 01:05:14,735
- <i>[Gasps]</i>
- Dibs!

866
01:05:14,810 --> 01:05:18,906
Wha...
[Groaning]

867
01:05:21,817 --> 01:05:25,378
[Screaming]
[Screaming]

868
01:05:25,655 --> 01:05:28,180
What is all this?

869
01:05:28,257 --> 01:05:30,851
My dad's lab.
Kind of a slob,
wasn't he?

870
01:05:30,927 --> 01:05:34,590
Down here, he could do
whatever he wanted to.
But no matter how busy he was,

871
01:05:34,630 --> 01:05:37,656
he would drop everything
to play pirates with me.

872
01:05:37,733 --> 01:05:40,133
<i>Man, we had</i>
<i>so much fun.</i>
[Gasps]

873
01:05:40,202 --> 01:05:44,866
Aye, matey.
Buccaneers and buried gold.
Whipstaff doth a treasure hold.

874
01:05:44,941 --> 01:05:46,909
Oh!
Come on.

875
01:05:48,978 --> 01:05:50,912
Dibs!
Oh!

876
01:05:50,980 --> 01:05:54,746
So where's this
Lazarus thing?
<i>You're lookin'at it.</i>

877
01:05:54,817 --> 01:05:58,651
Down there?
Huh. That's useful.

878
01:05:58,721 --> 01:06:01,986
Oh, I know there's a way
to get it going.
I just can't...

879
01:06:02,058 --> 01:06:05,027
What about that?
That?

880
01:06:05,094 --> 01:06:07,255
Nah. That's the vault.

881
01:06:07,330 --> 01:06:10,026
[Gasps]
[Gasps]

882
01:06:10,099 --> 01:06:12,624
Wait!
It's gotta be this!

883
01:06:15,137 --> 01:06:17,071
[Grunts]

884
01:06:18,140 --> 01:06:21,268
[Grunts,
Frustrated Growl]

885
01:06:21,344 --> 01:06:23,278
[Grunting]

886
01:06:49,872 --> 01:06:53,535
<i>[Rumbling,</i>
<i>Bottles Rattling]</i>

887
01:07:18,234 --> 01:07:20,168
Hey, I did it!

888
01:07:41,290 --> 01:07:43,224
Lazarus!

889
01:07:45,928 --> 01:07:48,829
[Grunting]

890
01:07:48,898 --> 01:07:51,059
[Grunting Continues]
[Exasperated Sigh]

891
01:07:51,133 --> 01:07:53,067
Ah. Ooh. Ouch.

892
01:07:54,336 --> 01:07:56,270
[Grunts]

893
01:07:57,840 --> 01:08:00,308
[Steam Hissing]

894
01:08:13,222 --> 01:08:15,190
What is this?
Careful!

895
01:08:15,257 --> 01:08:17,623
That's what makes
the whole thing work.

896
01:08:17,693 --> 01:08:20,389
Kind of an instant
primordial soup mix.

897
01:08:21,497 --> 01:08:23,965
It's what brings ghosts
back to life.

898
01:08:25,334 --> 01:08:27,325
Just enough for one.

899
01:08:41,484 --> 01:08:43,679
- Pull the lever.
- Which one?

900
01:08:43,752 --> 01:08:45,686
I don't know.
Try one.

901
01:08:56,699 --> 01:09:00,965
- Casper?
- I'm gonna be alive.

902
01:09:01,036 --> 01:09:05,336
[Door Creaking]

903
01:09:06,542 --> 01:09:08,476
<i>[Latch Clicks]</i>

904
01:09:10,279 --> 01:09:13,248
Oh, man, how am I
gonna do this?

905
01:09:13,315 --> 01:09:16,250
I couldn't even get
my Easy Bake oven to work.

906
01:09:18,888 --> 01:09:21,413
<i>[Clanging]</i>

907
01:09:23,759 --> 01:09:25,693
Okay.

908
01:09:30,032 --> 01:09:34,332
[Whistles Blowing]

909
01:09:54,890 --> 01:09:56,824
Casper?

910
01:10:10,773 --> 01:10:12,707
Am I alive?

911
01:10:15,611 --> 01:10:18,546
Dibs, do you have any idea
what this means?
Yes!

912
01:10:19,949 --> 01:10:23,680
No.
You don't have to be scared
of death anymore.

913
01:10:23,752 --> 01:10:26,220
One minute you'll be a ghost;
next, you're back on your feet,

914
01:10:26,255 --> 01:10:28,689
free to come and go
as you please.

915
01:10:28,757 --> 01:10:31,817
